## 1. Purpose
This procedure defines how [COMPANY] determines whether an impermissible use or disclosure of unsecured Protected Health Information (PHI) constitutes a reportable **breach**, and how it notifies affected individuals, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS/OCR), the media, and — as a Business Associate — affected Covered Entities, in accordance with the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule (45 CFR §§ 164.400–414).

## 2. Scope
Applies to any suspected or confirmed acquisition, access, use, or disclosure of unsecured PHI not permitted by the HIPAA Privacy Rule, in any form (electronic, paper, verbal), across all [COMPANY] systems and workforce. "Unsecured PHI" means PHI not rendered unusable, unreadable, or indecipherable through encryption or destruction per HHS guidance — properly encrypted PHI generally falls under the **safe harbor** and does not trigger notification.

## 3. Relationship to Incident Response
This procedure is invoked **from** the Incident Response Plan (`../resilience/incident-response-plan.md.template`) whenever an incident involves, or may involve, PHI. The IR process handles containment, eradication, and recovery; this procedure handles the **regulatory determination and notification** obligations that run in parallel. [COMPANY]'s role — Business Associate vs. Covered Entity — determines who notifies whom (see §7).

## 4. Step 1 — Discovery & Escalation
1. Any workforce member who suspects a PHI breach **shall** report it immediately to the [Privacy Officer] / [Security Officer] (see incident reporting channels).
2. A breach is treated as **"discovered"** on the first day it is known, or by exercising reasonable diligence would have been known, to [COMPANY]. **The notification clock starts on the date of discovery, not the date of confirmation.**
3. The [Privacy Officer] convenes the breach response team: [Privacy Officer, Security Officer, Legal/Counsel, Comms, executive sponsor].

## 5. Step 2 — Breach Risk Assessment (the four-factor test)
An impermissible use/disclosure of PHI is **presumed to be a breach** requiring notification **unless** [COMPANY] demonstrates a **low probability that the PHI has been compromised**, based on a documented risk assessment of at least these four factors (45 CFR § 164.402):

1. **The nature and extent of the PHI** involved (identifiers, likelihood of re-identification, clinical sensitivity).
2. **The unauthorized person** who used the PHI or to whom it was disclosed.
3. Whether the PHI was **actually acquired or viewed**, or merely had the opportunity.
4. The extent to which the **risk to the PHI has been mitigated** (e.g., recipient attestation of destruction).

Also evaluate whether one of the three **regulatory exceptions** applies (unintentional good-faith access by workforce; inadvertent disclosure between authorized persons at the same entity; good-faith belief the unauthorized recipient could not retain the information). Document the assessment and conclusion regardless of outcome, and retain it (see §9).

## 6. Step 3 — Determination
| Outcome | Action |
|---|---|
| Encrypted/safe-harbor PHI | Not a breach; document rationale; no notification. |
| Low probability of compromise (documented) | Not a reportable breach; document and retain assessment. |
| Reportable breach | Proceed to notification (§7) under the applicable timelines. |

## 7. Step 4 — Notification

> **CRITICAL — know your role.** If [COMPANY] is a **Business Associate**, its primary obligation is to notify the affected **Covered Entity** without unreasonable delay and **no later than 60 calendar days** from discovery; the Covered Entity generally then notifies individuals/HHS/media. **The BAA may require notification far sooner (e.g., 24–72 hours)** — the BAA terms control. If [COMPANY] is acting as a **Covered Entity**, the obligations below apply directly.

| Recipient | When | How |
|---|---|---|
| **Affected Covered Entity** (if BA) | Per BAA, else ≤60 days from discovery | [Method per BAA] |
| **Affected individuals** (if CE) | Without unreasonable delay, ≤60 days from discovery | Written notice by first-class mail (or email if agreed); substitute notice if contact info is insufficient/out of date for ≥10 individuals |
| **HHS/OCR** — ≥500 individuals | Contemporaneously with individual notice, ≤60 days | HHS breach portal |
| **HHS/OCR** — <500 individuals | Within **60 days of the end of the calendar year** | HHS breach portal (annual log submission) |
| **Prominent media** — ≥500 in a state/jurisdiction | Without unreasonable delay, ≤60 days | Press release to major media outlets serving the area |

**Content of individual notice (45 CFR § 164.404(c)) must include:** a brief description of what happened and the date of breach/discovery; the types of PHI involved; steps individuals should take to protect themselves; what [COMPANY]/the CE is doing to investigate, mitigate, and prevent recurrence; and contact procedures (toll-free number, email, or postal address).

## 8. Step 5 — State Law & Contractual Overlays
[COMPANY] **shall** also evaluate, with counsel, obligations under applicable **state breach-notification laws** (which may cover broader data, impose shorter deadlines, or require notice to state AGs/credit bureaus) and any **contractual** notification clauses. Apply the **strictest** applicable requirement. [List the states most relevant to your customer/patient base here.]

## 9. Step 6 — Documentation & Retention
All breach assessments, determinations (including "not a breach" decisions), notifications, and supporting evidence **shall** be documented and retained for at least **six (6) years** per HIPAA documentation requirements (45 CFR § 164.316(b)(2)). [COMPANY] bears the **burden of proof** that required notifications were made or that an impermissible use/disclosure did not constitute a reportable breach.

## 10. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Privacy Officer] | Owns this procedure; leads the breach determination; coordinates notifications. |
| [Security Officer] | Provides technical investigation; bridges to the IR Plan. |
| [Legal / Counsel] | Confirms regulatory and state-law obligations; reviews notices. |
| [Comms] | Drafts individual/media notices and press releases. |
| All Workforce | Report suspected breaches immediately. |

## 11. Exceptions
None. Notification obligations are regulatory and may not be waived by internal exception.

